I know this thread is old, but since folks are still posting here, I might as well put in my thoughts:<br>
<br>
I'd really like to see a MMORPG with the same fantasy based theme like EQ, such as a wide variety of race/class combos you can choose from. But my MMORPG will have a sort of similarity to Grand Theft Auto. What I mean by that is, each race/class combo has a set storyline to follow through a series of quests. And just like Grand Theft, you DON'T have to follow the set story, you can freely run around and do whatever you want, as endlessly as you want and accept &quot;side quests&quot; that have nothing to do with your race/class storyline. Each race/class will also have a different &quot;end boss&quot;, an when you kill the &quot;end boss&quot; you get a nice little cinematic &quot;ending&quot; sequence with credits, just like a console RPG. Also, any player characters that helped you kill your &quot;end boss&quot; will get to see your ending as well.<br>
<br>
So pretty much, my MMORPG will still be a MMORPG because you DON'T have to follow a set story like EQ, you can make the game as endless as you want; it will be like Capcom's Street Fighter Alpha series because you can choose a wide variety of characters that have a different end boss and different ending; it will be like a console rpg because you can follow a linear storyline with an ending; and it will be like Grand Theft Auto because you can do whatever you want in between storyline quests. <br>
<br>
Another thing I'd add to my MMORPG is: lvling up will be a lot quicker. Sheez, it takes approximately one month or less to reach lvl 60 in Final Fantasy, or any other console rpg. But in EQ? Could take about 4 months to a year depending on how much time you put into the game, and come on now, people have lives ya know. I'd make sure that the game is designed to a point where: if you put in approximately 20+ hours a week playing the game, you'd get to lvl 60 in about two months or less. And with so many race/class combos to choose from, and different endings to see along with countless side quests, it'd have lots of replay value to keep the customers paying the monthly bill.<br>
<br>
